The following new lead was qualified by Dave at Software Advice. Please feel free to mention Dave's name when you first contact the prospect. Questions about this lead should be sent through the Customer Support App. Replies to this email will not be received.
 
Contact Information
Company name: M.B. Kahn
Contact name: Kara Soles
Job title: Vice President of Business Development
Direct: (803) 227-5236
Email: ksoles@mbkahn.com
Website: http://www.mbkahn.com
Address: 101 Flintlake Road
City: Columbia
State: SC
ZIP code: 29223
Country: United States
Timestamp: 5/31/16 10:13 CDT
 
Company Profile
Segment: Construction - B2B. Industrial construction company that takes on $5M-$100M projects. They self perform some of the work. This is just the industrial division of a larger company. They offer commercial design/build services as well.
Size (Annual Revenue): $51 million to $100 million
Number of Employees: 101 to 500 employees
Number of Users: 2 to 5 users. 3 users to start out. This may roll out to other divisions as well, but for now they're concerned with the industrial division.
 
Project & Requirements Overview
Applications needed: Sales Automation
Key features needed: This buyer wants a system that will track upcoming projects, track sales meetings, track interactions, tag contacts, and pull reports.
Deployment: Not Determined
Currently using: They used to use Act!, but they haven't had it for several years. They use Gmail internally, but many of the people there are synched with Outlook.
Reasons for shopping: Kara was recently brought on to help get the sales efforts organized, and this is one of the big priorities currently.
Who they've evaluated: Act!.
Price expectations: Screened for $80/user/month plus setup costs.
Timeframe: They want to get something in place within a few months.
 
Next Steps
Request: Demo
Product: Cosential
Follow-up instructions: Call between 4 and 5:30 EST.
Contact notes: Kara was tasked by a senior vice president to find something for the core business development team.
Qualified By: Dave

No CRM. Very old school mentality. Tracking leads/opps of most importance. Not too many in depth proposals, more letter proposal types and FOQ. Heavy lead/opp, outlook integration, mobile app, email marketing. Billquick is their accounting software. 3-8 people start with 2 full users and the rest would be CRM users. Driving adoption and getting people to use it is key. Move slow and don't overwhelm with all the bells and whistles. Kerri is a consultant but it seems she'll be working side by side with Stacy Malone as they will both be full users. Demo set for 5/31 at 4pm.

Reasons for shopping:    He wants to bring in a CRM solution for his sales guys to track communication with clients easier and more efficiently.
Who they've evaluated:    SalesForce, Dynamics, Hitachi Solutions.
Price expectations:    $125/user/month and $1K/license upfront plus setup costs.
Timeframe:    Next 3 months.

Company Profile

Project & Requirements Overview
Applications needed:    Sales Automation
Key features needed:    Manage separate pipelines for leads that are design only, build only, or design and build. They want to input incoming leads, send email blasts, and track communication through the system. The field sales team needs access through iPads. It would be nice if the system has advanced features such as a website landing page, social media integration, and lead generation.

Reasons for shopping:    Apptivo does not offer an iPad app. They are also unable to link tasks and activity to the related contact.
Who they've evaluated:    HubSpot.
Price expectations:    Screened up to $75/user/month plus setup.
Timeframe:    Immediate.

Slam dunk Disco call - They have a home grown DB which they were about to sink another 50-60k into getting it updated so that it actually works.  This DB held current bids and company info.

This client is a perfect fit for Cosential and they are jazzed about it.  Multiple office locations would all be represented in Cosential so there is high potential for good seat counts.  

The have folks that do bids, and folks who do proposals.  Initially they said that their proposals were too custom to have done by us, but I explained how we dynamically pull in custom opp fields and they are now hopeful that they too can leverage Proposal Automation. Not sure I remember what Acctg system they use.  

 

Interested in more information. Sees the benefit of a CRM but not sure if the company is willing to invest. She used to do BD but has moved into a slightly different role. Requested brochure and open to talking further. Disco set for Andy on 4/20.

3 companies. Bottom level. Concrete ready mix plant. 

2nd tier is harkins concrete construction. That company works for other contractors as well as Harkins contractors. Concrete construction company is often on site with other generals. Want to be able to share and manage lead and opportunities. She is the controller. Computer use is acct software? Might look at new acct software so it would be great to integrate but not a deal breaker. Dispatching software, command alcon. Customer info entered in there. Causes some disconnect. Plant, VP/operations manager. He is the main BD person. Assistant plant manager and dispatcher. Majority of business is people coming to them. 6-7 users to start.

In 2005, Alex Hernandez founded Hernandez Consulting in the aftermath of Hurricane Katrina to help with New Orleans’ re-building process. Utilizing the firm’s small and disadvantaged business certifications, Hernandez Consulting captured several contracts with federal agencies to provide construction, security and project management services. Since our origination, the firm has developed into a project management firm specializing in construction, architecture, real estate development, and sustainability and energy management consulting.

 

Headquartered in New Orleans, Louisiana; with two additional offices in Miami, Florida and Fayetteville, Arkansas; Hernandez Consulting operates throughout the Southern United States and beyond. Our Offices are staffed with highly trained construction and design professionals to include superintendents, project managers, estimators, architects and administrative personnel. 

 

 

 

Brief call with Andy to qualify and demo is set for 4/12.

Notes - Hello Jeff,

 

We currently use Procore as our construction mgt software and have used Insightly in the past, but to limited results.  We’re considering salesforce simply because I used in the past.  Do you have a demo package or software download to evaluate?  Or maybe a quick demo at our office?

 

Tucker
